<div class="text-wrap">
  <h3>Interviewing Methods</h3>
  <h6>Quantitative vs. qualitative</h6>
  <p>
    Quantitative is good for understanding what, where, and when. Qualitative
    is good for understanding why and how.
  </p>
  <h6>In-person vs. survey</h6>
  <p>
    Surveys are great for finding a consensus. In-person interviews are great
    for understanding someone’s thought process, emotions, and environment.
  </p>
  <h6>Which method to use?</h6>
  <p>
    If you’re just starting out with your research, user-interviews can be
    great. It can act as a blunt tool. Surveys are more like a surgical knife.
    They're a great opportunity to ask more specific questions that produce
    answers smaller in scope.
  </p>

  <h3>Sourcing interviewees</h3>
  <p>
    <a href="http://intercom.io">Intercom</a> is excellent for finding segments
    of existing customers based on their behavior with your product or website.
  </p>
