<div class="text-wrap">
  <p>
    Interview in pairs if possible. One person acts as the conversation lead
    which allows them to focus on what the interviewee is saying and where to
    dig in further with more specific questions.
  </p>
  <p>
    The second person acts as the note taker. They are focused on recording
    what the interviewee is saying. This means they can take the time to record
    more than just the words being said but also the emotions expressed, how
    long it took the interviewee to recall certain information, etc.
  </p>

  <h3>Background research</h3>
  <p>
    Research some biographical information about the person you're about to
    speak with. I ususally start by collecting the basics: photo, name, what
    they do, where the live, etc. Twitter is always good for that. With that
    info, you're armed with some info to be casual and friendly if you need
    something to get the convo started!
  </p>
  <p>
    It's also important to collect their most recent usage of your product.
    <a href="http://www.salesforce.com">Salesforce</a> with
    <a href="https://clearbit.com/salesforce">Clearbit</a>
    integrated is a quick stop for this. You can get an overview of any
    conversations/emails they’ve exchanged with your sales tea and support team.
  </p>

  <h3>Good conversation</h3>

  <h6>Like having a beer</h6>
  <p>
   A lot of the interview will come down to just having some good conversation.
   Don't worry about trying to get all the answers you need. Just be casual and
   be yourself. The interview should be fun! I always imagine the tone of the
   conversation being similar to grabbing coffee or beer with a friend.
  </p>
</div>

